\subsubsection{Mode}

The \emph{mode} is the most expected value in a distribution or the largest category of a variable is the most frequently occurring observation of this variable.

\begin{itemize}
\samepage
\item For example:

% Requires the booktabs if the memoir class is not being used
\begin{table}[htbp]
   \begin{center}
   %\topcaption{Table captions are better up top} % requires the topcapt package
   \begin{tabular}{@{} lllllllllllll @{}} \hline % Column formatting, @{} suppresses leading/trailing space
   % \multicolumn{13}{c}{\bfseries Ages of Urban Campus students} \\ \hline
       19 & 21 & 21 & 22 & 23 & \fbox{24} & \fbox{24} & \fbox{24} & 25 & 25 & 28 & 29 & 78 \\ \hline  
       
   \end{tabular}
   \end{center}
    \caption{Ages of STAT 2830 students}
   \label{tab:t3_6}
\end{table}
\samepage
\item The \emph{mode} is the most frequently occurring value in a dataset.  Since there are three of 24s, the \emph{mode} is 24.  While analyzing a dataset, we must use the mode for categorical data\footnote{A categorical data is a variable that can take on one of a limited, and usually fixed, number of possible values, thus assigning each individual to a particular group}  where we cannot use the mean or the median.   Think of the situation where we have 30 students in our classroom, and we survey them for the eye color and find there are 20 students with brown eyes, nine students with blue eyes, and one student with black eyes.  The brown eyes are the mode since brown eyes occur more frequently than the other colors.
\end{itemize}

