\section{Other Measures of Location}

The other measure of central tendency are as follows:

\begin{itemize} 
\samepage
\item Percentage: point below which a particular percentage of cases fall.
\samepage
\item Deciles: divides distribution into tenth (10, 20, $\dots$, 90).  For example, children's height in age groups.
\samepage
\item Quartiles: divides distribution into quarters ($Q_1 = 25$, $Q_2 = 50$, $Q_3 = 75$).
\samepage
  \begin{itemize}
  \item e.g., the median falls in the $50^{th}$ percentile (or the $2^{nd}$ quartile or the $5^{th}$ decile.)
  \end{itemize}
\samepage
\item Mid-range: $ MR = \frac{Minimum + Maximum}{2} $
\samepage
\item Mid-hinge: $ MH = \frac{Q_1 + Q_3}{2} $
\samepage
\item Calculate a percentile
	\begin{itemize}
	\item Sort scores in ascending order
	\item Multiply the number of cases (n) in the dataset by the proportional value of the percentile (for example the $90^{th}$ percentile is 0.9).
	
	\end{itemize}
		
	\item Example
		\begin{itemize}
		\item In a sample of 13 student ages from an urban campus (See Table 3.7), we want to find the $3^{rd}$ quartile (or the $75^{th}$ percentile),
		\item $13 \times 0.75 = 9.75$ is the $75^{th}$ percentile.  In this case, the $75^{th}$ percentile is located between the $9^{th}$ and the $10^{th}$ values in the list of 13, i.e., the third quartile is 25.
		\end{itemize}
		  	
\end{itemize}

